@node "Description" "Description of MagicBackdrops"
    MagicBackdrops is a set of 720×536 8-colour IFF ILBM pictures whose main purpose is to reside in the background of the Workbench screen. If you feel that there might be some other use for them, feel free to take advantage of that, but this was nevertheless the original intention. And what's so great about them? Well, nothing really, I just like them, and I wouldn't be all surprised if someone else does too. That's why I have bundled them together into this archive, and troubled myself writing these docs.

    All the images use the MagicWB 2.0 palette (or, are at least supposed to do so). They all have in common (as of this release) that they are scaled-up versions of already available pictures fetched from near and far. Because of this, the quality of all images isn't excellent, but most look fair. The worst ones aren't included in this distribution at all, and those who barely passed the quality test are distinguished from the rest in the descriptive texts below. The texts stating that an image is "cropped" mean that only part of the image is left, most of the times this is due to my pickiness about keeping the original pixel aspect ratio (thus getting rid of stretched-looking results). Most of the pictures are plain grayscales (however they all were more colourful before my tampering with them), but I felt that the Windows'95 logo just had to be an exception. :-)


    The picture (so far only one, yes) in the "Coloured/" drawer is currently:

    "Windows'95.Colour"
    This picture was a special one, I felt that it could use all the colours of the MWB palette; all eight of them. Still, it doesn't represent the original image very well; if you've seen the logo (haven't we all? <sigh>) you might know that the colours are red, green, blue and yellow, but I don't really care since it does quite an impact on some of my friends... The logo, name and company name are very likely to be copyrighted to Microsoft, so be careful when handling this one; Microsoft maybe won't like some free PR... ;-)


    The rest of the pictures are spread over the subdirectories "3-Grayscale" and "5-Grayscale" respectively. The criterias for what picture goes where should be pretty obvious. 3-Grayscale pictures have a more discreet 'look' and don't clash with the black colour normally utilized by people for icon text. 5-Grayscale images, however, do (to some extent), but instead they have greater 'depth' since a wider spectrum of the grayscale is used. If you feel uncomfortable with some of the pictures, don't use them!

    The pictures in the "3-Grayscale" directory are currently:

    "Artheel"
    A picture whose origin I don't know too much about, except for the fact that it was scanned by a "Mr M".

    "Charlotta"
    One of my favourites, featuring two of my friends from a summer vacation in southern France (Montpellier). The picture is a scanned version of a photograph taken on the beach "Miami", Palavas. This, by the way, is one of the few images who has been scaled neither up nor down.

    "DPG-920"
    The first of a huge bundle of Pamela Anderson pictures I found lying about. It was cropped and marginally punished by scaling. The DPG's comment is "Pamela Anderson, sexy in garter belt.".

    "DPG-1000"
    A DPG file, noted "Erika Eleniak, white T-shirt pulled up."; the image is lightly cropped.

    "DPG-1622"
    This one is a cropped and scaled-up version of the original DPG-1622.GIF file, which unfortunately took some nasty punishment in the process. The Digital Photo Gallery comments it as "Carolyn Jones, topless navy girl.".

    "DPG-1635"
    The reason why I MWBized (ugly but effective word) this picture is that a friend asked me to do so, so I did. "Tiffany and Tammy Rief, blonde sisters." is the Digital Photo Gallery comment for the original, unscaled picture.

    "DPG-1933"
    A horizontally flipped DPG image, commented "Sharon Stone, lying on a bed.".

    "DPG-2006"
    The DPG comment this one "Pamela Anderson, in denim shirt." - if I got the filename right, that is. Some people whom I know state that this isn't true, if you have any first-hand information of the correctness of this one, please tell me. The image was cropped and horizontally mirrored (if someone wonders why, the reason was that it fitted better on my Workbench that way).

    "DPG-2197"
    Quite low quality, due to cropping and scaling. The DPG says: "Pamela Anderson, in black panties.".

    "DPG-2531"
    The reason why this one is in the archive is that a friend of mine didn't care about its lousy quality (he's really fond of it), and thus I thought some of you might share his opinion. The DPG people say "Midi Miller, busty blonde." about it (this is a heavily cropped version, by the way).

    "Elite6"
    Unfortunately, this rather nice picture took some severe punishment in the scaling process. Still, I liked it enough to keep it. As of its origin, don't ask me; I haven't the slightest idea. The filename is preserved, though.

    "HoseShower"
    ...is like the above anotherone I MWBized for a friend of mine. I can't say much more of its origin than that the original file name was "WET-NL14.GIF", and that it originates from "Nitelog Imaging", (408) 655-1096.

    "Michelle"
    Yet another DPG image, however I don't have a clue of its original "serial number".

    "Niki Taylor"
    I believe this came from the same source, its file name was "NT-9509.JPG", and originates from some obscure calendar.

    "Paulina Poritzkova"
    ...is a picture I recieved from a friend half an hour before his OverDrive passed out (hi DEMF!). The name of the file was "PAULINA8.GIF" (is anybody really interested?).

    "Sanctuary"
    One of my favourites, drawn by Edward Barton. This version really doesn't do the original any justice at all; the amazing colouring is all gone, however it still makes for an impressive backdrop. Have a look at the original picture if you one day should stumble upon it.

    "Schneide"
    ...was drawn by Peach, for a party competition (can't say which one, where or when, but those who are interested in such information probably already know). Tried with 5 grayscales first, but felt that it looked better this way.

    "Teri Peterson"
    I may be wrong, but this was the filename when I recieved the picture. Probably it originates from the DPG, but I can't say I'm sure. The image is cropped and horizontally flipped.


    The pictures in the "5-Grayscale" directory are currently:

    "AHGP0438"
    "AHGP0439"
    "AHGP0444"
    These three pictures I know very little about. I found them on a disk long ago forgotten, and felt that this japaneese form of art (?) might want to be representated. Since all of the images are hand drawn using both black and white, I felt the need for a 5-grayscale palette.

    "Hajime-69"
    An odd-looking vine of grapes drawn by Sorayama Hajime, which didn't turn out too well, however, I still like it.

    "Windows'95"
    ...and finally the last image, that Windows'95 logo without that bad colouring scheme.
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "What is required to use this package?"
    The MagicBackgrounds package requires the MWB palette, and a large screen with a pixel aspect ratio near 1:1. DoublePAL 720×550 is my native screen mode, and it is for this all these images have been designed (720×536 actually, since my border eats 14 pixels vertical space). To use this package in conjunction with OS2.x, the NickPrefs package is recommended. OS3.x users should have no problems setting up WBPattern to do the job. Another recommended addition to your hardware is some additional memory; as much Chip memory as possible and preferrably some Fast too; the backdrops eat quite a lot of chipmem, but you don't @{i}have@{ui} to by any means.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage of MagicBackgrounds"
    Users of OS2.x should get hold of the NickPrefs package and use WBPicture to set up the backgrounds.

    3.x users don't need additional programs, since WBPattern is quite sufficient. Just tell WBPattern what picture(s) to use.
@endnode

@node "How" "How do I make my own Magic Backdrops?"
    First of all, you'll probably need a program similar to ADPro; I doubt very much that anyone wants to do a picture like this manually. This explanation assumes you have a copy of ADPro up and running.

    This step by step guide shows you how to make the grayscale backdrops (or rather how @{i}I @{ui}made these ones).

    1. The first step would probably be to find a picture that you like, and feel that you'd want to use. Preferrably, it should be larger than or equal to the size of your Workbench screen. This is the most troublesome step, especially if you decide to draw one from scratch yourself, but that is all up to you.
    2. Now load ADPro.
    3. Set the render screen to whatever screenmode used by your Workbench screen, the number of colours should be eight. If you have several pictures you consider converting, locking the screenmode and depth could be convenient.
    4. Turn on dithering, Floyd-Steingberg should be enough for most people.
    5. Load the picture into ADPro.
    6. If the image has some kind of border you don't want in the finished picture, it is time to crop it now.
    7. In case the picture is smaller than the desired screenmode, scale it up, making sure you keep the pixel aspect ratio intact (or correcting it if necessary).
    8. Run the "Colour to gray" operator.
    9. Load the MagicWorkbench palette (or grab it from your workbench). If you don't have it, load it from one of the pictures in this archive.
    10.Swap the first and fourth colours.
    11.Lock the palette.

    To make a 3-grayscale picture, keep reading here, for 5-grayscale images, skip the next section.

    12.In the Palette Control window, Set the number of used colours to three, and the "offset colour zero" to three as well.
    13.Run the "Dynamic Range" filter, setting the Minimum/Maximum values to 115/183.
    14.Render the picture. If you find the dark/light sections too dark/light, go back to the previous step, reducing the range. For a start, try 120/175.
    15.Save your finished picture!

    To make a 5-grayscale image, keep reading here.

    12.In the Palette Control window, Set the number of used colours to five, and the "offset colour zero" to one.
    13.Render the picture.
    14.Save your finished picture!
@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Known bugs"
    Well, any real "bugs" probably don't exist in this package, largely because there are no executable files included. However, someone might notice an incorrect colourmap or something similar, but so far I haven't found any. If anyone does, don't hesitate to contact me.
@endnode

@node "To do" "Yet to be done"
    Well, what is missing in MagicBackgrounds?

    All I can think of is additional backdrops of your preference, since I have run out of fresh images... If there is a picture you really like which you would like to have "converted" to this style, contact me! It isn't all unlikely I might do it for you, if you can't do it yourself.

    Any other ideas and suggestions are very welcome as well.
@endnode

